summary.name: Iowa Electricity Generation
summary.dataset_description: This dataset contains information about electricity generation in Iowa from different sources between 2001 and 2017.

properties.description: The year in which the electricity was generated.
The source of electricity generation (Renewables, Nuclear Energy, or Fossil Fuels).
The net amount of electricity generated in a given year, measured in thousand megawatt-hours (MWh).

goals.question: What is the trend in net electricity generation over the years?
goals.visualization: line chart of net_generation over year
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there has been an increase or decrease in electricity generation over the years.

goals.question: What is the proportion of electricity generated from each source?
goals.visualization: stacked bar chart of net_generation by source over year
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the contribution of each source to the total electricity generation in Iowa.

goals.question: What is the distribution of net electricity generation for each source?
goals.visualization: box plot of net_generation by source
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread and central tendency of net electricity generation for each source.

goals.question: What is the correlation between net electricity generation and year?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of net_generation over year
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is a relationship between net electricity generation and year.

goals.question: What is the distribution of net electricity generation?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread and central tendency of net electricity generation in Iowa.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['year'])]
    data['year'] = data['year'].dt.year

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.lineplot(x='year', y='net_generation', hue='source', data=data)
    plt.title('What is the trend in net electricity generation over the years?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend(title='Source')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['year'])]
    data['year'] = data['year'].dt.year

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.barplot(x='year', y='net_generation', hue='source', data=data, ci=None)
    plt.title('What is the proportion of electricity generated from each source?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend(title='Source', loc='upper left')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['year'])]

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    ax = sns.boxplot(x='source', y='net_generation', data=data)
    ax.set_title('What is the distribution of net electricity generation for each source?', wrap=True)
    ax.set_xlabel('Source')
    ax.set_ylabel('Net Generation (MWh)')

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
